# SWOT Analysis â€“ Workforce Attrition Project

This SWOT analysis evaluates the organization's workforce situation based on insights from the attrition data.  
It highlights internal strengths and weaknesses, as well as external opportunities and threats related to employee retention.

---

## Strengths

- Strong retention among long-tenure employees (Attrition: 10.42%)  
- Research & Development shows relatively stable workforce (13.84% attrition)  
- Employees with better work-life balance tend to stay longer  
- Higher-paid employees show lower attrition risk  

These indicate the organization can retain talent when engagement, compensation, and role stability are strong.

---

## Weaknesses

- High overall attrition rate (16.12%)  
- Very high attrition among Sales Representatives (39.76%)  
- Early-tenure employees leave frequently (25.96%)  
- Overtime employees show extreme attrition (30.53%)  
- Lower satisfaction among employees who left  

These weaknesses point to onboarding gaps, burnout, and role pressure issues.

---

## Opportunities

- Improve onboarding programs for new hires  
- Redesign Sales role workload and incentive structures  
- Implement workload management and overtime control  
- Introduce engagement and wellness initiatives  
- Review compensation competitiveness  

Targeted interventions can significantly reduce attrition risk.

---

## Threats

- Continued loss of skilled employees  
- Rising recruitment and training costs  
- Burnout affecting performance  
- Talent poaching by competitors  
- Reduced employee morale  

If unaddressed, attrition can weaken organizational performance and stability.

---

## Strategic Summary

The organization has strong foundations for employee retention, but high turnover in early-tenure and high-pressure roles presents a strategic risk.  
By addressing workload, onboarding, compensation, and engagement, the company can transform workforce stability into a competitive advantage.
